{"name":"Grammar","id":67,"content":"<p>Use of commas:</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">For building set of subjects e.g. A, B, and C means {A, B, C}. The set can be seen as composite subject.</p>\n\n<div class=\"tool__example tool__incorrect\">\n<p class=\"tool__example-content\" style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">In complex predicates:</p>\n\n<div class=\"tool__example-content\" style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Incorrect: I meant to buy tickets for Cleo&rsquo;s show, but ran out of time.</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"tool__example tool__correct\">\n<div class=\"tool__example-content\" style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct:&nbsp;&nbsp; I meant to buy tickets for Cleo&rsquo;s show but ran out of time.</div>\n\n<div class=\"tool__example-content\" style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Exceptions: Cleo spotted the man who entered the diner, and waved. <em>(because it is needed to clarify the message)</em></div>\n</div>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">When you want to join two independent clauses, you need a <a href=\"https://www.grammarly.com/blog/conjunctions/\">conjunction</a> or a <a href=\"http://www.grammarly.com/blog/2016/semicolon/\">semicolon</a>. A comma alone isn&rsquo;t strong enough to join them. This kind of mistake is called a <a href=\"https://www.grammarly.com/blog/comma-splice/\">comma splice</a>.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Incorrect: We were out of milk, I went to the store.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct: We were out of milk, so I went to the store.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct: We were out of milk; I went to the store.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct: We were out of milk. I went to the store.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">After Intrductory phrases:</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct: Grabbing her umbrella, Kate raced out of the house. Confused by her sister&rsquo;s sudden change in mood, Jill stayed quiet.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct: After the show, Cleo will be signing autographs. Behind the building there is enough space to park two limousines. Without knowing why, I crossed the room and looked out the window. In 1816 life was very different. Suddenly, an angry black cat sprang from the shadows.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct: Before eating, the family said grace. <em>(because it is needed to clarify the message)</em></p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Instead of parenthesis:</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct: The weather, I was happy to see, was beginning to clear.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Before but if it is joining two independent sentences:</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Incorrect: Cleo is a good singer but she&rsquo;s an even better dancer.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct: Cleo is a good singer, but she&rsquo;s an even better dancer.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Incorrect: My teacher is tough, but fair.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct: My teacher is tough but fair.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Incorrect: The cafe, that Chester recommended, is a fantastic restaurant. <em>(Because the &#39;that Chester recommended&#39; part is essential, so it should not seem parenthetical)</em></p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Correct: The cafe that Chester recommended is a fantastic restaurant.</p>\n\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://writingcenter.unc.edu/tips-and-tools/semi-colons-colons-and-dashes/\" target=\"_blank\">Use of Semicolon, Colon and Dashes</a></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","authorId":null,"subject":"hidden","tags":null,"img":null,"summary":null,"lastUpdated":"2020-03-24T05:39:35.573+0000"}